{"/service/ndnp/fu/batch_fu_hastings_ver02/data/sn95047334/00529042401/1937121601/0852.xml":{"full_text":"Page Two\n\u25a0M|]]\u00bbNind^\nhi<\nSnl bv hssl\nmmSwp ciuiiMeLin\nConfusion and Discord: There is\nmore confusion and less hartiony\nin Washington today than at any\ntime since March, 1933.\nThe Senate and House are at\ncomplete variance on the Farm\nBill. Neither House is in accord\nwith the Secretary of Agriculture\nnor the President, and the indica\ntions are that the Secretary and\nthe President are not fully agreed.\nThe feeling between the North\nand the South over the anti-lynch\nbill is bitter and, as the day for\nfinal action approaches, the situa-\n\"Would Be's\"\nmo the \"Will Be's\u201d\nThere are two classes of people\nin the world\u2014the \u201cwould be\nrich\u201d who are always wishing,\nand the \u201cwill be rich\u201d who are\nsteadily saving. In which class\neare you?\nWe invite you to join the\n\u201cwill be\u2019s\u201d by opening and\nbuilding up a savings account.\nCitizens Bank Trust Co.\nQUINCY FLORIDA\nMEMBER FEDERAL DEPOSIT INSURANCE CORPORATION\nJE&ivPiy\niwbefler liqhT^T\n^^^beHer tighter\nThe Ideal\nCHRISTMAS GIFT\nYOUR most perplexing gift prob\nlem is now solved with one of these\nmodern I. E. S. glareless Lamps. These\nnew, scientifically designed I. E. S.\nLamps provide just the right amount of\n'glareless illumination to prevent eye\nstrain. Shop at our store or your Lamp\nDealer\u2019s for I. E. S. Lamps the\nideal Christmas gift for 1937.\nBNow On Sale By Your^^\nFavorite Lamp\nDealer\n\u2014lll\u2014\u2014\u2014 1111.1\nFLORIDA POWER\nCORPORATION\ntion becomes more tense. That\nunfortunate piece of legislation,\nconceived in an effort to secure\nvotes in the northern centers, is\nproving a stumbling block in the\nway of important business.\nI Almost as great difference ex\nists between the two Houses of\nCongress on the wages and hours\nbill, as exists the case of the\nagricultural bill. The bill passed\nin the Senate and that to be con\nsidered in the House are widely\ndifferent. On the surface of things,\nJohn L. Lewis, of the C. I. 0., and\nWilliam Green, of the A. F. of L.,.\nappear to be supporting the wage\nand hour legislation. Actually, the\n1 opposite is generally believed to be\n\u2018true. The House Committee has\nagreed to abandon the proposal to\ncreate a separate and independent\nBoard to administer the law and\nurge an amendment placing it in\nthe Department of Labor. This is\nnot a great deal more pleasing to\nthe South than the original pro\nposal. The violent opposition to\nthe creation of any more boards is\noffset by a deeprooted objection\nto the manner in which the Labor\nDepartment has handled labor re\nlations.\nIt is unfortunate that the Con\ngress is delaying action on the\ntax bill. It is now generally admit\nted by those who sponsored the\nundistributed profits tax bill and\nthe capital gain tax bill that they\nhave not only string-halted busi\nness but have reduced the total of\nFederal taxes. Immediate action\nshould be taken on these matters\nin an effort to halt the present\nbusiness recession. The experts\nsay that if industry is convinced\nearly action will be taken on the\ntax bills an enthusiastic and cour\nageous expansion program may\nbe expected with resultant new\norders and reemployment.\nInternational Complications: The\nnewspapers continue to carry stor\nies of incidents in the Japanese-\nChinese trouble which are of im\nportance to the United States in\ndetermining its future diplomatic\npolicies.\nSeizure by the Japanese Naval\nforces of the American-owned\nsteam tug Feiting did little to\ni.armonize harsh differences. The\nJapanese hauled down the Ameri\ncan flag, threw it into the Whang\npoo River and then deliberately\ntowed the tug down the river past\nthe U. S. cruiser Augusta. The re\nturn of the tug, after our State\nDepartment\u2019s protest, helped some.\nThe conservative Washington\nPost, discussing the Shanghai si\ntuation in its editorial column, re\ncently said: \u201cFor sheer, unmiti\ngated gall the attitude of Japan\nregarding the Chinese maritime\ncustoms at Shanghai sets a new\nrecrod.\u201d\nNotwithstanding the protests of\nthe United States, Great Britain\nand France against Japan\u2019s seiz\nure of the customs at China\u2019s\ngreatest port, the Tokyo foreign\noffice indicated that Japan will\ncontinue to act independently, with\nout consulting other powers, and\nwithout giving consideration to\nthe rights and interests of other\nnations.\nApparently Japan feels that by\nhaving defeated the Chinese at\nShanghai she has also defeated\nthe Western nations which have\nholdings there.\nThe International situation is\nbecoliing evep more tense and our\nState Department finds it neces\nsary to exercise great caution in\ndealing with it.\nAction On REA: Definite prog\nress is being made on Rural Elec\ntrification for the Third District.\nThe Jackson-Calhoun Counties\nproject will be the first to get un\nder way, with the Walton-Holmes\nproject in line for approval as\nsoon as money is available.\nBoth projects will, according to\nthe REA, be approved on a partial\nbasis, and then expanded from\ntime to time to meet the need.\nSince it has net been possible\nfor the REA to make acceptable\ncontracts with power companies\non wholesale power, considerable\nfunds are to be spent in the erec\ntion of generating plants. It had\nbeen hoped this would not be re\nquired as the money, necessary to\nbe used for generating machinery,\ncould have been allocated to line\nconstruction.\nCOUNTY SALE OF TAGS\nINCREASES $5,809.32\nMrs. J. M. Rowan, Gadsden\ncounty tax collector, and auto tag\nagent for the State license depart\nment, reports her office sold 41,-\n611.84 worth of car licenses for the\nyear ending December 1.\nThis is an increase of $5,809.32\nover the 1936 period, when her of\nfice sold $35,802.52 worth of tags.\nEWOLE\nJACKSONVILLE\nJ FLORIDA\nGARNETT ANDREWS,Mmm\nENJOY COMFORT at this\nmodern, fireproof hotel in the\nheart of downtown Jackson\nville. Every room with tub and\nshower, soft water, ceiling fan,\nradio, slatted summer door\nEvery Bed with innerspring\nmattress and reading lamp.\nRunning ice water on every\nfloor.\nAIR CONDITIONED\nCOCKTAIL LOUNGE COFFEE SHOR\nDINING AND MEETING ROOMS\nr fatw-Sugh wKh IMvm M -1'\nI T\u00bb Rom. $2 00 so Room $2.50 1\nI 40 Rmm S3jOO 24R00m $1 JO I\n|IE fa^l. Rom. RHm. M s4o*\nH^IIL RATTEN y HOTEL DESOK\nGADSDEN COUNTY TIMES\nNeedy Youths Be\nAssisted by NYA\nNew Ruling Will Give Young Men\nand Women Chance to Earn\nSome Money.\nThere are many needy youths in\nFlorida who will welcome the good\nnews that the former regulations\ngoverning the selection of those\nwho could work on NYA projects\nhave been broadened to include\nhundreds who up to this time have\nbeen shut off from NYA jobs.\nFormerly only those young peo\nple between the ages of 18 and 25\nwho were members of WPA famil\nies receiving commodities or other\nforms of public assistance were\neligible for NYA employment. A\nrecent ruling broadens the grounds\nfor certification and in addition to\nthese former groups, young men\nand women may now have NYA\njobs whose family income is be\nlow the subsistence standard.\nEven though the head of the\nfamily has a small private job or\nis farming for himself, if the in\ncome is below the figures set by\nthe welfare board the youths in\nthese families may be certified for\nNYA only. This means that young\npeople in non-certified families\nmay now be certified for the train\ning, work experience and wages\nthat NYA supplies.\nIf young men and women in\nGadsden county wish to increase\ntheir work experience and obtain\nsome much needed cash they can\nconsult Miss Eva Morris, care of\nSocial Welfare office, Quincy, and\nlearn if they are eligible for NYA\nwork. Miss Morris will give advice\nand counselling to all applicants.\nLarge numbers of vacancies on\nNYA projects were occasioned by\nboys and girls returning to school\nthis fall, so work opportunities\nare open to those who are interest\ned and can qualify under this new\nruling.\nOffice days for applications are\non Mondays and Thursdays from\n9 a. m. to 1 p. m.\nMETHODIST STUDENTS\nTO ATTEND MEETING\nMiss Pauline Flake, of Quincy,\nis one of five members of the\nMethodist student organization at\nthe Florida State College for Wo\nmen, Tallahassee, who on Decem\nber 28-31 will attend the Nation\nal Methodist Student convention in\nSt. Louis.\nOther delegates include Miss\nMarie Lewis, Umatilla; Miss Jane\nDowdell, Wiauma; Miss Esther\nO\u2019Byme, Lake Wales, and Miss\nAlice Royster, representing Trini\nty Methodist church in Tallahas\nsee.\nAccompanying the students from\nthe college will be Miss Frances\nBaker, Methodist student secre\ntary.\nMiss Margaret Holway, of New\nPort Richey, is president of the\nMethodist student body at the col\nlege.\nMiss Flake is a daughter of Mr.\nand Mrs. A. W. Flake, who reside\non a farm near Quincy.\nChristmas Seal your Christmas\nmail.\nJEWELRY\ngiwhsh\nMany Practical and Worthwhile Gift Items Included in the Following Suggestions:\nFor Milady: For Him:\nWatches, Diamond Rings Pocket and Strap Watches\n^*o^ Yellow Gold Bracelets Belt Buckle Sets\nVanity Sets Bill Fold Sets\n-am Pen and Pencil Sets\nComb Brush Mirror Sets Watch Chains O\nFolding Traveling Sets Rings A fl\nFitted Bags Tie Holders fu\nFountain Pen Sets Bags m\nFOR THE HOME: 11 I\nSilver of All Kinds Photo Frames Floor Lamps Ag\nDresden Novelties Pictures Italian Pottery H i\nCONBOY W\nJEWELER M|\nCOUNTERFEIT SOCIAL\nSECURITY CARDS OUT\nBusiness men over the state have\nbeen warned by Harold C. Wall,\nTallahassee, director of the unem\nployment compensation division of\nthe Florida Industrial Commission,\nto be on the lookout for counter\nfeit social security account cards\nbeing used for identification.\n\u201cThe taere possession of an ac\ncount card,\u201d says Mr. Wall, \u201cdoes\nnot necessarily mean that the hold\ner is the person to whom it was is\nsued, nor is it indicative of the\nfinancial responsibility of the hold\ner.\u201d\nQuality I\nGIFTS\nNORITAKE CHINA\nsi\nBavarian and American All size sets; also open stock patterns.\n1\nZENITH America\u2019s most copied Long Dis\ntance Radio.\nAlways a year ahead. Table Models\u2014Armchair Models\u2014Consoles.\n1\nELECTRIC TOASTERS Percolators\nWaffle Irons... Sandwich Toasters... Heaters\nIrons... Heating Pads. 1\nBoys\u2019 All Steel Roller Bearing Wagons (all sizes)\nBicycles, Tricycles, Watches, Knives, Boy\nScout Hatchets, Air Rifles, Target Air Pistols,\nMarble Games, Footballs, Roller Skates.\nBURLINGTON America\u2019s most beautiful line of BASKETS.\nWe have mentioned only part of our Christmas goods. Call and see them. 1\nYou will find quality at the right price.\nBell Bates Hardware i\nCompany\nGIVE AN\na There\u2019s an Ingersoll fi\nfor every member I\nof the family\nwatches for pocket, Wk 11\nwrist or handbag at If\nprices from 51.25.\nYou can buy them fifejHdMwM\nat stores right here\nin town. g\nRIST-ARCH\u2014S3.9S YANKeT^*\n^\u00a3SejnberlB, uJ","height":"22846","width":"15600"}}
